You are an expert in extracting accurate information from clinical trial protocols.

## Task ##
Identify and extract all **Primary Efficacy Assessments** mentioned in the trial, along with their key attributes.

## Field Definition ##
A **Primary Efficacy Assessment** refers to the main measurement(s) used to evaluate whether the investigational treatment achieves its intended therapeutic effect compared to control.  
Each Primary Efficacy Assessment entry should include its name, a short description of what it measures or how it is defined, and the frequency or schedule at which it is assessed.

## How to Identify ##
- Focus on the **primary efficacy endpoints or assessments** specified in the protocol.
- They are usually listed in sections such as:
  - “Objectives and Endpoints”
  - “Efficacy Assessments”
  - “Synopsis” (under “Endpoints” or “Efficacy Endpoints”)
  - “Schedule of Assessments” or “Time and Events Table”
- Look for phrases like:
  - “Primary efficacy endpoint”
  - “Primary efficacy assessment”
  - “Efficacy will be assessed by / measured using / evaluated using”
  - “Defined as” (indicating assessment definition)
- Include any scoring systems, clinical scales, biomarkers, or objective measures used to evaluate efficacy.
- Exclude:
  - Secondary or exploratory endpoints
  - Safety assessments (e.g., adverse events, lab safety panels)
  - General statistical endpoints (unless they describe a clinical measurement)

## Field Extraction Rules ##
For each **Primary Efficacy Assessment**, extract:
- **assessment_name** – Exact name of the measure or endpoint (e.g., Full Mayo Score, HbA1c, RECIST Response, PASI75).
- **assessment_short_description** – Brief explanation of what the assessment measures or how it is defined (e.g., “Composite score assessing stool frequency, rectal bleeding, and endoscopic findings.”),. Use exact verbatim and exact text present in content.
- **assessment_frequency** – When and how often the assessment is performed (e.g., “At baseline and Week 12”, “Every 4 weeks during treatment”). Don't include any extra text in this, it should only be telling about time, frequency,  range, and related terms may be there like - approx, prior, etc.

## Output Format (JSON) ##
{
  "primary_efficacy_assessments": [
    {
      "assessment_name": "<Exact name of the efficacy assessment as stated in the protocol>",
      "assessment_short_description": "<Brief explanation of what it measures or how it is defined>",
      "assessment_frequency": "<Timepoints or schedule when it is assessed>"
    },
    {
      "assessment_name": "<Exact name of the efficacy assessment as stated in the protocol>",
      "assessment_short_description": "<Brief explanation of what it measures or how it is defined>",
      "assessment_frequency": "<Timepoints or schedule when it is assessed>"
    },
    ...
  ]
}

## Additional Notes ##
- If multiple phrases refer to the same assessment (e.g., “Full Mayo Score” and “Mayo Disease Activity Index”), merge them into one entry, but don't repeat anything.
- Maintain one unique entry per assessment.
- Ensure all extracted snippets preserve original protocol wording exactly.
- If there is name of the assessment, then there should be assessment_short_description, don't leave assessment description empty if assessment name is present and vice versa.
